    "_id": "689d8ab52fb30d3059aca225",
    "title": "Remote Work and Productivity: A Mixed-Methods Review",
    "content": "IntroductionRemote work has transitioned from being a rare perk to a widespread organizational practice. This shift, accelerated by global events such as the COVID-19 pandemic, has prompted researchers and managers alike to reassess its impact on productivity.MethodologyThe present review utilized a mixed-methods design, integrating data from quantitative surveys involving over 1,200 participants and qualitative interviews with 35 employees and managers from various industries.FindingsQuantitative InsightsSurvey results indicated that 68% of respondents reported a productivity increase of at least 10% when working remotely three or more days per week. Commonly cited factors included reduced commuting time and flexible scheduling.Qualitative InsightsInterviews revealed that while autonomy improved focus, inadequate communication tools and blurred work-life boundaries could negatively affect outcomes.“Remote work has given me the space to focus deeply, but sometimes I feel disconnected from my team,” said one participant.DiscussionThese results suggest that productivity gains are not inherent to remote work itself, but rather to the environment and resources that support it. Organizations must invest in robust communication platforms and clear policies to sustain long-term benefits.ConclusionRemote work has the potential to enhance productivity, provided that employers address challenges such as isolation, technology gaps, and the need for clear expectations.",
